+            # Zero-coefficient aux term — every requires_grad param participates
+            # in the autograd graph, so backward() produces grad=0 (not None)
+            # for any param whose normal forward path was empty this iter.
+            # Forward contribution to the loss value is exactly 0.0.
+            #
+            # Why this matters: the cluster of bugs we used to band-aid
+            # around (GradScaler "No inf checks" assertion, DDP zero-loss
+            # collapse from asymmetric stepping, 60-min NCCL watchdog
+            # timeout from rank-asymmetric grad sets, fp16 has_grad fragility)
+            # all reduce to "some DDP rank has params with .grad=None this
+            # iter while others do not". This aux term forces every rank's
+            # autograd graph to be topologically identical: every param has
+            # a path back to the loss. Adam treats grad=0 as no-op (m, v
+            # coast on prior signal, identical across ranks → no DDP drift).
+            #
+            # Compiler robustness: we use a runtime-allocated zero scalar
+            # (torch.zeros((), ...)) rather than a Python ``0.0`` literal,
+            # so torch.compile / TensorRT / similar JIT pipelines cannot
+            # constant-fold the multiplication away and prune the graph
+            # connection. The autograd ENGINE in eager-mode PyTorch handles
+            # ``0.0 * x`` correctly (the MulBackward node always visits x),
+            # but inference compilers can be more aggressive about DCE.
+            zero_coef = torch.zeros((), device=loss.device, dtype=loss.dtype)
+            loss = loss + zero_coef * sum(
+                p.sum() for p in self.model.parameters() if p.requires_grad
+            )
